\v 13 But the man who had been healed¦66613 didn't even know who it was, because when a crowd had formed, Jesus¦66623 had quickly left.
\p
\v 14 Later on, Jesus found the man in the temple and told him, “Look, you're better now, so don't sin because you don't want anything worse to happen to you.”
\p
\v 15 The man¦66665 then went¦66661 and¦66666 told the leaders that it was Jesus who had made him¦66682 better.
\v 16 As a result, the leaders started harassing Jesus because he had done this on a rest day¦66706.
\v 17 But Jesus just replied, “My father¦66715 is working today, and¦66720 so I'm also working.”
\p
\v 18 Because of this, the leaders became determined that he must be put to death, not just because he broke the rules for the rest day¦66739, but especially because he was calling God his own father¦66742, thus making himself equal to God!
\s1 Authority over life is given to the son
\p
\v 19 So Jesus responded to them, “I want to tell you all something: The son can't initiate anything by himself. He can only do what he sees his father doing, because whatever his father is doing, he also does things like that.
\v 20 You see, the father¦66813 loves his son and shows him everything that he's doing. In fact, he'll be showing him even greater things than what he's done already, so that you all will be amazed.
\v 21 Because the father¦66845 brings the dead back to life, giving them new life, so also the son can give life to whoever he wants.
\v 22 The father¦66866 won't be judging anyone, but¦66869 has already given that task to the son,
\v 23 so that the people might honour the son like they honour the father. But any who is not honouring the son, is also dishonouring the father who sent him.
\p
\v 24 “I assure you that whoever hears my message and believes that I was sent by God, will live forever and will not be condemned, but has moved from death into life.
\v 25 I can also assure you¦66934 that a time is coming, and in fact is here already, when the dead¦66943 will be hearing the voice of the son of God and that voice will bring them back to life.
\v 26 As the the father¦66962 is the source of life, he gave the power of giving life to the son
\v 27 and gave¦66985 him the authority¦66983 to be the final judge, because he is mankind's child.
\v 28 Don't be surprised at this, because a time is coming¦66999 when everyone in their graves will be hearing his voice,
\v 29 \x + \xo 5:29: \xt Dan 12:2.\x*and the ones having done what is good¦67024 will be given new life¦67028, and the ones having done what is evil¦67033 will be condemned.
\s1 The unbelief of the religious leaders
\p
\v 30 Jesus continued explaining to the religious leaders, “I don't do anything in isolation. As I hear from him, only then do I judge and my judgement is correct and impartial because I'm not imposing my desires, but the desire of the one who sent¦67073 me.
\p
\v 31 “If I just testify about myself, my testimony would not be correct or even valid.
\v 32 But it's another one that's testifying about me, and¦67093 I know that his testimony about me is true.
\v 33 \x + \xo 5:33: \xt Jn 1:19-27; 3:27-30.\x*You sent¦67107 people out to question John¦67109 and¦67110 his testimony was true.
\v 34 But I don't even need testimony that comes from people, because I am teaching you¦67128 how to be saved.
\v 35 John was a bright and shining¦67137 light¦67147 and you¦67138 appreciated it for a short time.
\v 36 But I have a stronger testimony than John's because the father has entrusted works to me to complete, and which I'm already doing and which clearly show that the father sent me here.
\v 37 \x + \xo 5:37: \xt Mat 3:17; Mrk 1:11; Luk 3:22.\x*And since he sent¦67192 me, he himself has testified about me. You people have never listened to his voice, nor have you ever seen¦67211 him!
\v 38 And his way of thinking is obviously not in your minds, because you don't believe the one that he sent.
\v 39 You look in the Jewish scriptures because you suppose that they'll lead you to eternal life¦67240. Those very scriptures testify about me coming,
\v 40 yet you refuse to come¦67256 to me in order to receive life¦67260.
\p
\v 41 “I'm not getting any praise from people
\v 42 but I do know that you people don't actually love¦67276 God in your hearts.
\v 43 I have come in my Father's name and you don't accept me, but if someone came in their own name, you'd happily accept them.
\v 44 How \em could\em* you possibly believe when you just accept acclamations from each other, but don't even seek praise from the only \add God\add*.
\v 45 But don't be assuming that I'll be accusing you all in front of the Father. No, the one who'll accuse you is Moses because he's the one that you're hoping you'll please.
\v 46 The trouble is that if you actually believed what Moses wrote, you would believe me, because Moses was writing about me.
\v 47 But since you don't really believe his writings, you're not at all likely to believe me.”
\c 6
\s1 The feeding of 5,000 families
\r (Mat. 14:13-21; Mrk. 6:30-44; Luk. 9:10-17)
\p
\v 1 After all this, Jesus crossed the lake \add in a boat\add*.\f + \fr 6:1 \ft Here John also uses the Roman name “Lake Tiberias” rather than just “Lake Galilee”.\f*
\v 2 A large crowd followed him¦67397 because they¦67404 had seen his miraculous healings of sick people.
\v 3 Jesus climbed a hill and¦67425 sat there with his apprentices.
\v 4 At that time, it was getting close to the Jewish Feast of Passover.
\v 5 When Jesus looked out and¦67453 saw the large crowd coming, he asked Philip, “Where can we¦67467 get enough food from to feed all this crowd?”
\v 6 But he was only saying¦67478 this to test Philip because he already knew what he was going¦67486 to do.
\p
\v 7 Philip answered, “It would take quite a few months wages to buy even just a snack for this many people.”
\p
\v 8 Now one of Jesus' apprentices, Simon Peter's brother, Andrew, said to Jesus,
\v 9 “There's a boy¦67521 here with five¦67527 buns and¦67530 two¦67531 small cooked fish¦67532, but¦67533 that wouldn't even start to feed this crowd.”
\p
\v 10 But Jesus told them to get all the people¦67547 to sit down as there was a large grassy area. So they all sat down—some five¦67569 thousand men¦67563 were counted.
\v 11 Then he took the buns and gave thanks to God, and started passing around both the buns and the fish¦67597, and everyone ate as much as they wanted.
\v 12 Once everyone was full, Jesus got his apprentices to collect the left-over fragments so as not to waste anything.
\v 13 So they gathered¦67618 the left-overs and filled twelve¦67626 baskets with left-over bread.
\p
\v 14 The people¦67642 who had witnessed this and other miracles said, “This really is the prophet that God promised to send!”
\v 15 But Jesus¦67665 knew that they intended to come and grab him to announce him as their king, so he moved out of the crowd and on up the hill.
\s1 Jesus comes walking across the lake
\r (Mat. 14:22-33; Mrk. 6:45-52)
\p
\v 16 As it¦67694 moved into evening, Jesus' apprentices went back down to the lake
\v 17 and having boarded the boat¦67707, they¦67708 set out across the lake toward Capernaum. By then it was dark, and there was still no sign of Jesus.
\v 18 Then a strong wind hit the lake and the water got rough.
\v 19 When they had rowed about five¦67756 kilometres, they saw Jesus¦67761 walking¦67762 on top of the lake and approaching the boat¦67771, and they were very scared.
\v 20 But he told them, “Don't worry—it's me.”
\v 21 After that they were willing to let him into the boat, and immediately the boat was at their arrival place.
\p
\v 22 The next day, the crowd looked across the lake and saw that only one small boat had crossed, and they knew that only Jesus' apprentices had boarded that boat and left, and not Jesus himself.
\v 23 Other boats¦67874 came¦67872 across from Tiberias near the place¦67885 where they¦67888 had eaten the bread¦67890 after the Master had given thanks.
\v 24 So when all the people saw¦67897 that Jesus wasn't around and his apprentices had left, they went off looking for Jesus in Capernaum.
\s1 The bread that enables true life
\p
\v 25 When they found him there across the lake, they queried, “Teacher¦67942, when did you come¦67947 here?”
\p
\v 26 And Jesus answered, “Honestly, I know that you're looking for me, not because you saw¦67962 miracles, but because you all had plenty of food to fill you up.
\v 27 Don't \add just\add* work for the food which goes off, but¦67982 for the food which lasts forever, which mankind's child will give to you¦67996 because God the Father has put his mark of approval on Acts”
\p
\v 28 Puzzled, they asked him, “What should we be doing if we want to do God's work?”
\p
\v 29 He answered, “Doing God's work is putting your trust in the one that He sent¦68041 here.”
\p
\v 30 “If so,” they said, “what miracle will you do for us to see¦68057 so that we can believe in you? What can you do?
\v 31 \x + \xo 6:31: \xt Exo 16:4,15; Psa 78:24.\x*Our ancestors ate the manna out in the wilderness, as Moses wrote, ‘He gave¦68080 them bread¦68076 from heaven¦68079 to eat.’ ”
\p
\v 32 Jesus said to them, “Actually I can tell you that it wasn't Moses who gave them bread from heaven, but my father¦68105 gives you the real bread from heaven,
\v 33 because the bread¦68119 of God is the one who came down from heaven¦68128 and¦68129 who gives life¦68130 to the world.”
\p
\v 34 So they¦68136 requested, “Mister¦68140, always give¦68143 us that bread.”
\p
\v 35 But Jesus answered, “\em I am\em* the bread¦68157 that gives life¦68159—whoever comes to me will never hunger, and¦68170 the one believing in me, will never be thirsty again.
\v 36 But as I said¦68182 already, although you have seen¦68186 me you refuse to believe me.
\v 37 Everyone that the Father gives to me will come to me, and¦68202 I certainly won't turn away anyone who comes to me,
\v 38 because I came¦68214 down from heaven¦68218, not to do what I want, but¦68227 to do what the one who sent¦68231 me wants.
\v 39 And what He wants is for me to not lose any that he's given to me, but¦68254 to bring them back to life on the last day¦68262.
\v 40 My father¦68272 wants everyone¦68277 who watches me and believes in me to live forever, because I will bring them back to life¦68289 on that last day¦68299.”
\p
\v 41 This little speech made the religious leaders grumble about him because he had said¦68308 that he was the food that came down from heaven¦68317,
\v 42 as they figured out, “This is Jesus the son of Joseph and so we know his parents. So how can he say that he come down from heaven¦68353?”
\p
\v 43 Jesus scolded them, “Don't be grumbling to each other.
\v 44 No one can join me unless the Father who sent¦68380 me attracts them, and¦68386 then I'll be bringing them back to life on the last day¦68394.”
\v 45 \x + \xo 6:45: \xt Isa 54:13.\x*The prophets wrote that the people will be taught by God. And everyone who's heard and¦68414 learned from the Father comes to me.
\v 46 Not that any person has seen the Father—only the one who came from God has seen Acts
\v 47 I tell you¦68446 sincerely: the one who believes \add in me\add* will live forever.
\v 48 I am the bread¦68458 that gives true life¦68460.
\v 49 Your ancestors ate manna in the wilderness, but they¦68475 all went on to die.
\v 50 I am the bread¦68479 that came down from heaven¦68483 and¦68493 whoever eats this will not die.
\v 51 I am the living bread that came down from heaven¦68507 and if anyone eats this bread, he will live through to the next age.”
\p
\v 52 At this point, the religious leaders began to argue with each other, “How could this man give¦68562 us his flesh to eat?”
\p
\v 53 So Jesus explained, “Indeed if you don't eat my flesh and drink my blood¦68596, you aren't truly alive!
\v 54 The person who eats my flesh and drinks my blood¦68620 will gain eternal life—I will bring them back to life on the last day¦68632.
\v 55 For my flesh is the true food, and¦68641 my blood¦68643 is the true drink.
\v 56 Whoever eats my flesh and drinks my blood¦68693 lives in me, and I will live in him.
\v 57 The father is alive and sent me here, and I am alive because of Him, so also the person who eats me will be alive because of me.
\v 58 Unlike your ancestors who ate that bread and then died, whoever eats this bread that came down from heaven¦68763 will live through to the next age.”
\s1 Many people find the teaching too difficult
\p
\v 59 Jesus taught all of this in the meeting hall there in Capernaum¦68797.
\v 60 But even many of Jesus followers who heard it said, “This is difficult teaching—it's too hard to take.”
\p
\v 61 But Jesus already knew inside that his followers were grumbling about this and asked them, “Do you¦68844 find this offensive?
\v 62 What if you were to see mankind's child ascending to where he came from?
\v 63 It's the spirit that is the source of life, not the body. The concepts that I've taught you are all spiritual and life-giving.
\v 64 But there are some here who don't believe me.” Actually, Jesus had already known from the beginning just who would believe and¦68912 which person would betray him.
\v 65 So he said, “That's why I told you that no one can come¦68931 to me unless the Father has given them to me.”
\p
\v 66 After this, many of his followers went¦68954 back and no longer accompanied him around.
\p
\v 67 So Jesus said¦68964 to the twelve¦68970, “Don't you also want to leave?”
\p
\v 68 \x + \xo 6:68-69: \xt Mat 16:16; Mrk 8:29; Luk 9:20.\x*Simon answered, “Master, if we went, who would we follow then? you're the \add only\add* one who teaches about living forever.
\v 69 We believe and¦68994 know that you¦68998 are the holy son of God.”
\p
\v 70 Jesus responded, “Didn't I choose all twelve¦69023 of you myself? And yet one of you is a devil.”
\v 71 (He was talking about Judas, son of Simon Iscariot, because he was the one who would go on to betray him.)
\c 7
\s1 Jesus' sceptical brothers dare him to go public
\p
\v 1 After all this, Jesus travelled around Galilee. (He didn't want to travel around Judea because the leaders there wanted to execute him.)
\v 2 \x + \xo 7:2: \xt Lev 23:34; Deu 16:13.\x*As it was now getting close to the Jewish Feast with Tents,
\v 3 his brothers¦69099 said¦69093 to him, “You should leave this place and go down to Judea so that all your followers can see the miracles that you're doing.
\v 4 You don't do things¦69143 out of the main stream if you want to become well-known. If you want to do miracles, show yourself to the wider world.
\v 5 (You see, not even Jesus' own \add half-\add*brothers believed \add that he came from God\add*.)
\p
\v 6 So Jesus responded, “Well, you guys can do that any time, but it's not the right time for me yet.
\v 7 All the people won't hate you¦69189 guys, but¦69191 they do hate me because I teach about the evil¦69203 things they are doing.
\v 8 You all go down to Jerusalem ahead of me. I'm not going¦69215 to the feast yet because it's not yet the right time¦69225 for me.”
\v 9 After saying this, Jesus stayed up in Galilee.
\s1 Jesus starts teaching about authentic justice
\p
\v 10 But after his \add half-\add*brothers had left to go down to Jerusalem, Jesus also went—not in the public limelight but just incognito so to speak.
\v 11 However at the celebrations, the Jewish religious leaders were searching for him, and were asking around where he was.
\p
\v 12 Even among the crowds there was a lot of quiet banter with some saying that Jesus is a good man and others complaining that he was misleading the people.
\v 13 Either way, no one was speaking¦69309 out in public about him, because they were afraid of the reaction of the religious leaders.
\p
\v 14 Finally sometime in the middle of the celebrations, Jesus¦69329 went¦69326 into the temple and¦69333 started teaching in there.
\v 15 Even the Jewish leaders were surprised, asking, “How can this man know so much when he hasn't been trained as a teacher?”
\p
\v 16 Jesus himself responded, “My¦69351 teaching doesn't come from me, but¦69360 from the one who sent¦69362 me.
\v 17 If anyone wants to do God's will, they'll soon figure out whether my teaching comes from God, or if I'm just making it¦69381 up myself.
\v 18 Any person who just teaches his own thoughts is just seeking their own advancement, but¦69398 whoever wants to promote the one who sent¦69403 them, this is authentic and¦69408 there's no hidden self-interest.
\v 19 Didn't Moses write down God's commandments for you, yet not a single one of you obeys them. Why are you wanting to execute me?”
\p
\v 20 “You must be demon-possessed,” said some in the crowd, “Who would be wanting to execute you.”
\p
\v 21 Jesus responded, “I did one miracle and you¦69457 were all amazed.
\v 22 \x + \xo 7:22: a \xt Lev 12:3; \xo b \xt Gen 17:10.\x*Moses gave you the commandment about circumcision (even though it actually came from before his time), but to obey this, you'll even circumcise a baby boy on the Rest Day.
\v 23 \x + \xo 7:23: \xt Jn 5:9.\x*So if a male can be circumcised on the Rest Day so that Moses' commandments aren't broken, they why did you get angry with me because I made a man healthy of the Rest Day?
\v 24 Don't just judge things so you yourselves look good, but¦69515 judge impartially, seeking the best for others.”
\s1 Could Jesus be the messiah?
\p
\v 25 After this, some of the locals from Jerusalem started asking, “Isn't this the man they¦69531 were wanting to execute?
\v 26 Here he is teaching in public, yet they're not even confronting him. Perhaps the leaders know that this really is the messiah?
\v 27 But we¦69558 even know where this man is from. Surely when the messiah comes, no one would know his family background.”
\p
\v 28 So as Jesus continued teaching, he called out, “Indeed you all know me and my home and family. But I didn't come¦69609 here of my own accord, but the one who sent¦69615 me here is truthful, even though you don't even know him.
\v 29 I know him, because I came from him, indeed, he was the one who sent¦69632 me here.”
\p
\v 30 So now they really want to arrest him, but no one touched him because it was not yet the proper time.
\v 31 Many in the crowd did believe that he was from God, and they were saying, “When the messiah comes, would he do greater miracles than what we've seen this man¦69687 do?”
\s1 Jesus discusses leaving as they aim to arrest him
\p
\v 32 The Pharisee party heard the crowd muttering about these things¦69700 and sent¦69702 out some of their servants along with the chief priests¦69706 to go and arrest Jesus.
\v 33 So Jesus said, “I'll only be with you¦69727 all for a short while longer and¦69729 then I'll be going¦69730 to the one who sent¦69733 me.
\v 34 You'll look for me but won't be able to find me, and you aren't able to go where I'll be going.”
\p
\v 35 The leaders wondered, “Where could he be going that we wouldn't be able to find him? Will he go and live with the Jews living among the Greeks and start teaching the Greeks?
\v 36 And what does he mean about looking for him and not being able to find him, and not being able to go where he goes?”
\s1 Jesus offers living water to the crowd
\p
\v 37 \x + \xo 7:37: \xt Lev 23:36.\x*On the final climax day¦69812 of the celebrations, Jesus stood there and shouted, “Anyone who's thirsty, come here to me and drink.
\v 38 \x + \xo 7:38: \xt Eze 47:1; Zech 14:8.\x*Whoever trusts me will have rivers of living¦69854 water¦69853 flowing out from him¦69851 just like the scriptures say.”
\v 39 He was talking about God's spirit that the ones who trust him would receive in the future—not yet because Jesus hadn't been lifted up to heaven yet. 
\s1 The people are divided about Jesus
\p
\v 40 When some in the crowd heard his teaching, they¦69906 said, “He really is the \add coming\add* prophet.”
\v 41 Others said, “He must be the messiah.”
\p But some pointed out, “The messiah won't come from Galilee.
\v 42 \x + \xo 7:42: \xt 2Sam 7:12; Mic 5:2.\x*Don't the scriptures say that he'll be a descendant of King David and¦69946 that he'll come from David's town of Bethlehem?”
\v 43 And so the crowd was divided about Jesus.
\v 44 Some \add of the servants\add* wanted to arrest him, but decided to leave him alone \add for now\add*.
\s1 The leaders distrust Jesus and mock his followers
\p
\v 45 So when servants returned back to the chief priests¦70001 and the Pharisees, they were asked, “Why haven't you¦70012 brought him?”
\p
\v 46 They answered, “We've¦70027 never heard anyone speak like he does.”
\p
\v 47 The Pharisees asked them, “Don't tell us that you've also been taken in by him?
\v 48 None of our leaders or any of us Pharisees believe that he's from God.
\v 49 But all these people ignorant of the scriptures are bewitched.”
\p
\v 50 \x + \xo 7:50: \xt Jn 3:1-2.\x*Now Nicodemus (the one who had previously visited Jesus) spoke up,
\v 51 “Since when did our rules allow us to judge a person before we've even heard them out and¦70108 investigated what they're doing?”
\p
\v 52 But they sneered, “And do you come from Galilee as well? Look in the scriptures and you'll soon see¦70131 that no prophet emerges out of Galilee.”
