\s1 The two witnesses of Jesus' authenticity
\p
\v 12 \x + \xo 8:12: \xt Mat 5:14; Jn 9:5.\x*Because of this, Jesus told them, “\em I am\em* the light of the world—whoever follows me won't walk in the darkness but will have the light of life¦70429.”
\p
\v 13 \x + \xo 8:13: \xt Jn 5:31.\x*Some from the Pharisee party argued, “You are testifying about yourself, so that testimony is invalid.”
\p
\v 14 Jesus responded, “Even when I am testifying about myself, my testimony is valid, because I know where I came¦70470 from and where I'm going.
\v 15 You all are judging according to your earthly values. I'm not judging anyone.
\v 16 But even if I was judging, my judgement would be correct, because it wouldn't just be me judging, but also the father¦70519 who sent¦70517 me.
\v 17 \x + \xo 8:17: \xt Deu 19:15.\x*It's even written in your¦70526 own laws that the testimony of two¦70531 men¦70532 is valid.
\v 18 So that's me testifying about myself, plus the father¦70552 who sent¦70550 me also testifies about me.”
\p
\v 19 “And where is your father?” they asked.
\p Jesus answered them, “You don't know either me nor my father. If you did know me, then you'd also know my father.”
\p
\v 20 He explained all this while he was teaching in the treasury part of the temple, but no one arrested him because the time for his \add suffering\add* had not yet arrived.
\s1 You can't go where I'm going
\p
\v 21 So he continued, “I will be going away and all of you will be looking for me, but you'll all just die in your sins and won't be able to go where I'll be going.”
\p
\v 22 This puzzled the Jewish teachers, “Surely he's not going to commit suicide! What else could he mean about ‘you can't go where I'm going to be going’?”
\p
\v 23 Jesus explained, “All of you¦70672 are from the world below, but I'm from the world above. You all are part of this world, but I'm not part of it.
\v 24 That's why I said that you'll be dying in your sins, because if you refuse to believe that I am \add God\add*, you will indeed be dying in your sins.”
\p
\v 25 “So who are you?” they asked.
\p And he answered, “Still just the same as I've been telling you from the beginning.
\v 26 I have a lot that I need to tell you all and to judge many of your actions, because the one who sent¦70745 me is true, and it's what I hear from him¦70755 that I speak to all people.”
\p
\v 27 (They didn't realise that he was talking to them about the father¦70767 \add in heaven\add*.)
\v 28 So Jesus told them, “When you all lift up\f + \fr 8:28 \ft lifted up / exalted: There's a play on words here. See https://bibleDifferences.net/2019/04/25/156-exulted (dead link???)\f* mankind's child \add on a pole\add*, then you will know that I am \add God\add*, and I don't do anything by myself, but I say all this just as the father¦70808 told me to.
\v 29 And the one who sent¦70815 me is with me—he didn't just leave me alone—because I am continually doing what pleases him.”
\p
\v 30 After he'd said all this, many people believed in him.
\s1 Jesus teaches about freedom from slavery
\p
\v 31 Because of this, Jesus told all the Jews who believed in him, “If you all continue to believe my message¦70858, then you're my true followers.
\v 32 You will have known the truth, and the truth will set you free.”
\p
\v 33 \x + \xo 8:33: \xt Mat 3:9; Luk 3:8.\x*But some queried, “We are Abraham's descendants and¦70884 we've never been slaves to anyone, so how can you¦70892 say that we'll be set free?”
\p
\v 34 And Jesus answered, “I can assure you all that anyone who sins is a slave to sin.
\v 35 And the slaves don't necessarily remain in the \add family\add* home forever—only the children have that right.
\v 36 So if the son sets you free, then you'll be truly free.
\s1 Jesus spars with the Jewish religious leaders
\p
\v 37 “Yes, I know that you're all descendants of Abraham, but you're trying to kill me because my message¦70963 doesn't lodge in you.
\v 38 Indeed I talk about what I've actually seen with the father, but you all are doing what you've heard from your father.”
\p
\v 39 But they retorted, “Abraham is our father.”\f + \fr 8:39 \ft father meaning ancestor. (Abraham lived some 2,000 years before the time of these events.)\f*
\p And Jesus responded, “Well, if you really were descendants of Abraham, you'd behave more like him.
\v 40 But instead you're trying to find a way to have me killed—to kill the man¦71035 who has spoken the truth to you—truth that I heard from God. Abraham never did that.
\v 41 you're doing what your father wants you all do to.”
\p But they shot back, “It's not us who was conceived by a couple that weren't even married! Anyway, we only have one father and that's God.”
\p
\v 42 Again Jesus responded, “If God was your father¦71088, you all would be loving me because I came¦71101 from God and for God. I didn't just come¦71111 by myself, but God sent¦71116 me here.
\v 43 Why can't you comprehend what I'm saying? The reason that you can't stand listening to my message¦71132
\v 44 is because you come from your father, the devil, and you want to do what \em your\em* father wants. But he was a murderer from the beginning, and doesn't stick to the truth because there's no truth in him. Whenever he tells lies, he's speaking from his own nature, because he's a liar and the source of lying.
\v 45 But because I'm speaking¦71189 the truth¦71188, you¦71193 don't believe in me.
\v 46 Which of you can scold me for my sins? If I am speaking¦71207 the truth¦71206, why don't you believe I'm from God?
\v 47 Anyone who belongs to God, listens to what God says. But you all can't even hear the message, because you don't belong to God.”
\s1 Jesus preceded, and is greater than, Abraham
\p
\v 48 The Jewish leaders asked, “Aren't we right in saying¦71245 that you're from Samaria and that you have a demon?”
\p
\v 49 “No, I don't have a demon,” Jesus answered, “but I honour my father¦71269 and¦71271 you're dishonouring me.
\v 50 But I'm not seeking greatness for myself—he is the one seeking and the one judging.
\v 51 I can assure you, that anyone who puts my teaching into practice can be certain to avoid death in \add this\add* age.”
\p
\v 52 The Jews said, “Now we \em know\em* that you have a demon! Abraham and the prophets all died, but you're saying¦71329 that those who follow your teaching can be certain to avoid death in \add this\add* age.
\v 53 How could you be greater than our ancestor Abraham who died? Even the prophets died. Who do you think you are?”
\p
\v 54 Again Jesus answered, “If I praise myself, my praise is worthless, but it's my father¦71384 who praises me—the one who you say is your God
\v 55 although in fact you don't even know him. But I have known him, and so I can't say¦71409 that I haven't known him or I'd better a liar like all of you. But I have known him and I am putting his desires into practice.
\v 56 Your ancestor Abraham would have been excited to see me here—in fact he did see ahead and was very happy about it.”
\p
\v 57 Because of that, the Jewish leaders asked, “You aren't even fifty¦71453 years old yet. How could you have seen¦71460 Abraham?”\f + \fr 8:57 \ft Abraham lived some 2,000 years before Jesus.\f* 
\p
\v 58 Jesus answered, “I can assure you¦71472 that \em I am\em*\f + \fr 8:58 \ft This awkward English is necessary to catch the play on words, because ‘I am’ is the meaning of \em Yahweh\em*, the name of God.\f* before Abraham ever existed.”
\p
\v 59 When they heard that, they picked up stones¦71481 to throw¦71483 at Jesus \add to kill him\add*. But Jesus was hidden from their sight, and went on out of the temple.
\c 9
\s1 A blind man obeys and then can see
\p
\v 1 As Jesus was walking along, he¦71505 saw¦71505 a man¦71506 who had been blind from birth¦71509
\v 2 and his followers asked¦71512 him, “Honoured teacher, why was this man¦71521 born blind? Was it because he himself sinned, or his parents?”
\p
\v 3 Jesus answered, “It was neither this man¦71535 nor his parents who sinned, but it was so that God can work in him for others to see.
\v 4 As long as it's daytime, we need to do what the one who sent¦71559 us wants. When night comes, no one will be able to work.
\v 5 \x + \xo 9:5: \xt Mat 5:14; Jn 8:12.\x*As long as I'm here in this world, I am the light¦71579 of the world.”
\p
\v 6 After he'd said¦71584 this, Jesus spat on the ground and after mixing some clay into a slurry, he spread it on the eyes¦71603 of the man
\v 7 and told him, “Now go and wash in the Siloam Pool.”\f + \fr 9:7 \ft Siloam means ‘to be sent out’.\f*
\p
\v 8 Then the neighbours of the man and others who had seen him earlier, knowing that he was a beggar asked, “Isn't he the one who always sat and begged here?”
\p
\v 9 And indeed, some were saying, “Yes, this is him.” But others were saying, “No, but he looks quite similar.”
\p And the man said, “I \em am\em* him.”
\p
\v 10 So they¦71673 asked him, “Well, how come you¦71686 can see now?”
\p
\v 11 “A man named Jesus made a slurry” he said, “and spread it on my eyes and told me to go and wash at Siloam Pool. So I went and did it, and when I washed my eyes, I could see.”
\p
\v 12 “Where is he now?” they¦71731 asked.
\p “I don't know.” said¦71731 the man.
\s1 The Pharisees can't accept the healing of the blind man
\p
\v 13 Then they brought the man¦71750 who had been blind to the Pharisees¦71747.
\v 14 Now, it¦71751 had been the Rest Day when Jesus had made the slurry and¦71764 enabled him¦71768 to see,
\v 15 and because of this, some in the Pharisee party asked him how it was that he could see now. And he answered, “Well, he put a slurry on my eyes¦71793 and when I washed them, I could see.”
\p
\v 16 So some of them said, “Clearly that man is not from God because he doesn't respect the Rest Day.”
\p However others said, “But if he's just a sinner, how could he do miracles like that?”
\p
\v 17 So they asked the man who had been blind, “Well, what do you have to say because it was your eyes¦71861 that he opened?”
\p “He must be a prophet,” the man said.
\p
\v 18 But some of the Jews weren't even sure that he really had been blind and could now see, so they called for his parents
\v 19 and asked¦71894 them, “You two say that this is your son and that he was born blind. If so, how come he can see now?”
\p
\v 20 His parents answered, “We know that he's our son, and we know that he was born blind.
\v 21 But as for how come he can now see, we don't know that. Nor do we know who healed his eyes¦71953. But ask¦71964 him—he's old enough to speak for himself.”
\v 22 (His parents said these things¦71970 because they were afraid of the Jewish religious leaders, because the leaders had already announced that anyone who said that Jesus was the messiah would get banned from all religious services,
\v 23 so that's why they had said, “He's old enough—just ask¦72009 him.”)
\p
\v 24 So the leaders summoned the man born blind a second time and commanded him, “Only praise God himself for this, because we know that that man is a sinner.”
\p
\v 25 “Well, I don't know whether or not he's a sinner,” said the man. “All I know if that I used to be blind but now I can see.”
\p
\v 26 They asked again, “What did he do to you? How did he open your eyes¦72078?”
\p
\v 27 And he answered, “I already told you that and you didn't even listen. Why do you want to hear it all again? Do you all want to become¦72105 his followers as well?”
\p
\v 28 Then they¦72109 insulted him¦72111 and¦72112 said, “You might be a follower of that man, but¦72123 we are followers of Moses.
\v 29 We know that God spoke to Moses, but¦72144 we¦72146 don't even know where this other fellow is from.”
\p
\v 30 The man responded, “Wow, that's pretty amazing. This man opened up my eyes¦72179, and you teachers don't even know where he's from!
\v 31 We know that God doesn't listen to sinners, but he listens to those who worship him and do what he wants.
\v 32 In all the centuries we never heard that a person could give sight to someone who was born blind.
\v 33 If this man¦72220 isn't from God, surely he¦72227 wouldn't be able to do that!”
\p
\v 34 They reacted, “You're just an ignorant sinner, and you think you can teach <em>us</em>!” Then they had him thrown out the door.
\s1 Spiritual blindness and hypocrisy
\p
\v 35 Jesus heard that they had thrown out the man who could now see, and when he found him, he said, “Do you believe that mankind's child \add came from God\add*?”
\p
\v 36 And the man answered, “Mister, who is he so that I can believe in him?”
\p
\v 37 “You've seen¦72301 him and heard him and he's speaking¦72305 to you right now,” said Jesus.
\p
\v 38 And the man responded, “I do believe, master.” Then he knelt down in front of Jesus.
\p
\v 39 Jesus said, “I came¦72334 into this world to dispense judgement, so that the people who can't see will be able to see, and¦72341 so that the ones who can see will become¦72346 blind.”
\p
\v 40 The Pharisees with him heard that and asked, “Are you saying that we're blind?”
\p
\v 41 “If you were blind,” Jesus replied, “you wouldn't be sinning, but since you all declare that you can see, then your sin remains.”
\c 10
\s1 The sheep know their true master
\p
\v 1 “Honestly I can tell you: It's not the person that enters the sheep¦72414 enclosure by the gate that is a thief and¦72422 robber, but¦72415 rather the one who climbs in a different way.
